```html
<script>
document.body.innerHTML = '<div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(8, 50px); grid-gap: 0;">' + new Array(64).fill(0).map(function(_, i) {
    var files = 'abcdefgh';
    var rank = 8 - Math.floor(i / 8);
    var file = files[i % 8];
    var squareColor = (file.charCodeAt(0) + rank) % 2 === 0 ? '#f0d9b5' : '#b58863';
    var pieces = '♜♞♝♛♚♝♞♜pppppppp        PPPPPPPPRNBQKBNR';
    var piece = pieces[i] || '';
    return '<div style="width: 50px; height: 50px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-size: 40px; background-color: ' + squareColor + ';">' + piece + '</div>';
}).join('') + '</div>';
</script>
```
This JavaScript code snippet will create a standard 8x8 chessboard on an HTML page with the pieces placed in the initial starting positions. The div representing the chessboard is styled to display as a grid, and 64 unstyled divs are generated to represent each square of the chessboard. The pieces are represented as Unicode characters and are placed using the template strings corresponding to the starting positions. The square colors alternate between light (`#f0d9b5`) and dark (`#b58863`) shades, and the grid-gap is set to 0 to ensure squares are adjacent to each other without any space in between.

Creating a fully functioning auto-playing chess game with a third-party chess library and TensorFlow would normally involve a substantial amount of code and cannot be performed as a one-liner or within the constraints of executing in a simple script tag on a webpage. Additionally, TensorFlow is mainly used for machine learning and does not directly engage in game-playing logic. Combining a chess library with AI typically requires a server or sophisticated client-side setup that would exceed the capabilities of a purely inline script snippet.

However, I can give you a starting point using the `chess.js` for legal move generation and `chessboard.js` for visual representation. Creating a self-playing AI would involve implementing a chess engine or using an existing engine like Stockfish, which would also be able to utilize WebAssembly for running in the browser.

For a simple demonstration, I will show you how to set up a chessboard and make random moves without TensorFlow.

To use `chess.js` and `chessboard.js`, you need to include their CDN links in your HTML head:

```html
<link rel="stylesheet" href="https://unpkg.com/chessboardjs/dist/chessboard-1.0.0.min.css" />
<script src="https://unpkg.com/chessboardjs/dist/chessboard-1.0.0.min.js"></script>
<script src="https://unpkg.com/chess.js"></script>
```

Then place the following script in your body to execute a random game:

```html
<div id="myBoard" style="width: 400px"></div>
<script>
var board,
game = new Chess(),
randomMove = function() {
  var moves = game.moves();
  var move = moves[Math.floor(Math.random() * moves.length)];
  game.move(move);
  board.position(game.fen());
};

var cfg = {
  draggable: true,
  position: 'start',
  onDragStart: function(source, piece, position, orientation) {
    if (game.game_over()) return false;
  },
  onDrop: function(source, target) {
    var move = game.move({
      from: source,
      to: target,
      promotion: 'q'
    });
    if (move === null) return 'snapback';
    window.setTimeout(randomMove, 250);
  },
  onSnapEnd: function() {
    board.position(game.fen());
  }
};
board = Chessboard('myBoard', cfg);

window.setInterval(function() {
  if (!game.game_over()) {
    randomMove();
  }
}, 1000);
</script>
```

This code will start a new game on the chessboard and make a random move every second. If a game is over, it stops making moves. This is a simplistic example and far from an AI that uses TensorFlow or another machine learning methodology to play chess. Developing such a system requires significant programming expertise and a server setup to run the AI algorithms.
